---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Case Studies - Lavelle Pty Ltd"
  description="Recent engagements: enterprise transformation at the ABC, Griffith University's award-winning WCMS program, CQUniversity headless CMS, the Cyber Security CRC and more."
>
  <!-- SUB-PAGE HERO -->
  <section class="subhero">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="subhero__crumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a> &nbsp;/&nbsp; <span>Case Studies</span>
      </div>
      <h1>
        Outcomes that <em>hold.</em><br />Across two decades and four sectors.
      </h1>
      <p class="subhero__lead">
        Five recent engagements drawn from twenty years of senior project
        delivery in media, higher education and cybersecurity research. Each one
        began with an organisation in difficult territory - a fixed external
        deadline, organised stakeholder resistance, a procurement that had to
        withstand probity scrutiny, or a program that needed senior governance
        brought back to it. Each one ended with the work shipped and the
        relationships intact.
      </p>

      <div class="case-index">
        <a href="#case-01" class="index-item">
          <div class="index-item__num">Case 01</div>
          <div class="index-item__client">Griffith University</div>
          <div class="index-item__year">WCMS · 2015-2016</div>
        </a>
        <a href="#case-02" class="index-item">
          <div class="index-item__num">Case 02</div>
          <div class="index-item__client">ABC</div>
          <div class="index-item__year">Analytics · 2024</div>
        </a>
        <a href="#case-03" class="index-item">
          <div class="index-item__num">Case 03</div>
          <div class="index-item__client">ABC</div>
          <div class="index-item__year">Content Exchange · 2024-2026</div>
        </a>
        <a href="#case-04" class="index-item">
          <div class="index-item__num">Case 04</div>
          <div class="index-item__client">CQUniversity</div>
          <div class="index-item__year">Sitecore · 2021-2023</div>
        </a>
        <a href="#case-05" class="index-item">
          <div class="index-item__num">Case 05</div>
          <div class="index-item__client">Cyber Security CRC</div>
          <div class="index-item__year">Salesforce + O365 · 2020-2021</div>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CASE 01 - GRIFFITH WCMS -->
  <section id="case-01" class="case-section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="case-header">
        <div class="case-num">01</div>
        <div>
          <div class="case-tags">
            <span class="tag tag--ochre">Project Recovery</span>
            <span class="tag">Higher Education</span>
            <span class="tag">Award winning</span>
          </div>
          <h2 class="case-title">
            From <em>three years</em> to twelve months - with every previously-resistant
            stakeholder group on board.
          </h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="case-body">
        <div class="case-narrative">
          <p class="case-pullquote">
            "The WCMS program defined the next decade of my career. Politically
            charged, expected to take three years, with organised resistance
            from architecture, security, development and the business
            simultaneously. We delivered it in twelve months - and every group
            that started against the program stood behind its outcome."
          </p>

          <h3>The situation</h3>
          <p>
            Griffith University - ranked in the global top two per cent, with
            five Southeast Queensland campuses and approximately fifty thousand
            students - needed to replace its enterprise web content management
            platform. The program had been forecast at two to three years.
            Multiple internal groups had material reasons to want it not to
            succeed: architecture, cybersecurity, development and major business
            stakeholders were each, in different ways, organised against it.
          </p>

          <h3>The approach</h3>
          <p>
            Built genuine technical fluency on the job - platform architecture,
            security requirements, integration dependencies - at a level that
            allowed real engagement with the architecture, cybersecurity and
            engineering groups rather than just process management around them.
            Re-scoped the delivery from first principles. Rebuilt the fractured
            stakeholder relationships one at a time. Established governance that
            surfaced the underlying conflicts instead of papering over them.
          </p>

          <h3>The outcome</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>
              Delivered in approximately 12 months against a 36-month forecast
            </li>
            <li>At a fraction of the originally anticipated cost</li>
            <li>
              Every previously-resistant stakeholder group endorsed the outcome
              publicly
            </li>
            <li>
              Awarded Griffith University's <strong
                >Senior Leadership Award</strong
              > for positive change across individuals, teams and the business
            </li>
            <li>
              Followed by a five-year mandate at Griffith delivering Adobe
              Experience Manager, Salesforce Marketing Automation and an
              enterprise Squiz Matrix replacement program
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <aside class="case-aside">
          <div class="case-metrics">
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">36→12</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Months forecast versus actual delivery.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">1</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">Senior Leadership Award.</div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">4</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Stakeholder groups: resistance to endorsement.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">5yr</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Follow-on mandate at Griffith.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="case-meta">
            <dl>
              <dt>Client</dt><dd>Griffith University</dd>
              <dt>Sector</dt><dd>Higher Education</dd>
              <dt>Role</dt><dd>Senior Project Manager</dd>
              <dt>Year</dt><dd>2015-2016 (delivery)</dd>
              <dt>Platforms</dt><dd>Enterprise WCMS</dd>
            </dl>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CASE 02 - ABC ANALYTICS -->
  <section id="case-02" class="case-section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="case-header">
        <div class="case-num">02</div>
        <div>
          <div class="case-tags">
            <span class="tag tag--ochre">Data Platform Migration</span>
            <span class="tag">Media &amp; Broadcasting</span>
            <span class="tag">Fixed external deadline</span>
          </div>
          <h2 class="case-title">
            Migrating a national broadcaster's audience analytics - <em
              >on schedule, without incident.</em>
          </h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="case-body">
        <div class="case-narrative">
          <h3>The situation</h3>
          <p>
            Google's sunset of GA360 created a fixed, externally-imposed
            deadline. The Australian Broadcasting Corporation - Australia's
            national public broadcaster, with approximately four and a half
            thousand staff across television, radio, digital and on-demand
            platforms - needed to replace its core digital analytics platform
            without losing audience insight continuity in any business unit, on
            any platform, at any point. Around one hundred staff across product,
            data and engineering had to be coordinated through the change.
          </p>

          <h3>The approach</h3>
          <p>
            Led the end-to-end program under direct governance from the Chief
            Information and Digital Officer. The work spanned platform
            migration, event tracking and tagging rebuild across the entire web,
            mobile and app estate, SDK upgrades across mobile / tablet /
            connected-TV environments and the creation of new analytics data
            models and dashboard visualisations in Superset and Power BI.
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>
              Migrated the data platform from GA360 to Snowplow within six
              months
            </li>
            <li>
              Rebuilt event tracking and tagging across web, mobile and app
              stacks
            </li>
            <li>
              Upgraded SDKs across mobile, tablet and connected-TV environments
            </li>
            <li>
              Developed new analytics data models and dashboards in Superset and
              Power BI
            </li>
            <li>
              Coordinated approximately one hundred staff across product, data
              and engineering
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3>The outcome</h3>
          <p>
            Completed on schedule. No incidents at cutover. Full audience
            insight continuity preserved across every business unit and every
            distribution platform. CIDO governance maintained throughout.
          </p>
        </div>

        <aside class="case-aside">
          <div class="case-metrics">
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">6mo</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                From start to cutover, against an externally-set deadline.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">~100</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Staff coordinated across product, data and engineering.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">0</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Reported incidents at cutover.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">CIDO</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Direct executive governance throughout.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="case-meta">
            <dl>
              <dt>Client</dt><dd>Australian Broadcasting Corporation</dd>
              <dt>Sector</dt><dd>Media &amp; Broadcasting</dd>
              <dt>Role</dt><dd>Senior Project Manager</dd>
              <dt>Year</dt><dd>2024</dd>
              <dt>Platforms</dt><dd>Snowplow, Superset, Power BI</dd>
            </dl>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CASE 03 - ABC CONTENT EXCHANGE -->
  <section id="case-03" class="case-section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="case-header">
        <div class="case-num">03</div>
        <div>
          <div class="case-tags">
            <span class="tag tag--ochre">Business Case &amp; Procurement</span>
            <span class="tag">Media &amp; Broadcasting</span>
            <span class="tag">Restricted RFP</span>
          </div>
          <h2 class="case-title">
            Authoring the business case - and running the 15-person panel - for
            a <em>national broadcaster's</em> next-generation content distribution.
          </h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="case-body">
        <div class="case-narrative">
          <h3>The situation</h3>
          <p>
            The ABC's content distribution sat on a fragmented landscape of
            bespoke point-to-point integrations - costly to maintain, brittle to
            change and unable to support new content forms at the cadence the
            organisation needed. Two related decisions had to be made and
            defended: approve and fund a governed, event-driven internal content
            distribution capability ("Content Exchange") and select a
            next-generation podcast content management platform via restricted
            RFP.
          </p>

          <h3>The approach</h3>
          <p>
            Authored the full business case for CIDO delegate approval - problem
            statement, initiative objectives, benefits framework, risk register,
            delivery approach and key milestones. Concurrently managed the
            end-to-end procurement for the podcast platform: a restricted RFP
            targeting suppliers with demonstrable large-scale media experience.
            Designed a structured 70:30 technical-to-financial weighted
            evaluation methodology. Ran a fifteen-person evaluation panel
            spanning technical, finance, commercial and information security
            functions, with supplier clarifications, demonstrations, commercial
            negotiations, BAFO and delegate approval.
          </p>

          <h3>The outcome</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>
              Content Exchange business case approved at CIDO delegate level
            </li>
            <li>
              First approved use case - Audio Visualisation - in active delivery
              June to December 2026
            </li>
            <li>
              Fifteen-person evaluation panel reached consensus on supplier
              selection
            </li>
            <li>
              Probity-compliant evaluation process appropriate to public-sector
              audit standards
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <aside class="case-aside">
          <div class="case-metrics">
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">15</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Member evaluation panel: technical, finance, commercial,
                infosec.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">70:30</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Technical-to-financial weighted evaluation methodology.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">1</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Business case approved at CIDO delegate level.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">BAFO</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Through commercial negotiation to delegate approval.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="case-meta">
            <dl>
              <dt>Client</dt><dd>Australian Broadcasting Corporation</dd>
              <dt>Sector</dt><dd>Media &amp; Broadcasting</dd>
              <dt>Role</dt><dd>Senior Project Manager</dd>
              <dt>Year</dt><dd>2024-2026</dd>
              <dt>Type</dt><dd>Business case + Restricted RFP</dd>
            </dl>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CASE 04 - CQUNIVERSITY SITECORE -->
  <section id="case-04" class="case-section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="case-header">
        <div class="case-num">04</div>
        <div>
          <div class="case-tags">
            <span class="tag tag--ochre">Enterprise Delivery</span>
            <span class="tag">Higher Education</span>
            <span class="tag">Director-level advisory</span>
          </div>
          <h2 class="case-title">
            Replacing a multi-campus university's corporate website without
            disrupting <em>recruitment, alumni or brand.</em>
          </h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="case-body">
        <div class="case-narrative">
          <h3>The situation</h3>
          <p>
            CQUniversity - twenty-plus campuses, a QS five-star overall rating,
            and one of Australia's most accessible and engaged universities -
            needed to replace its corporate web platform without breaking
            ongoing recruitment, alumni engagement or brand activity. Five
            functional groups had to be kept aligned through the program: brand,
            marketing, international recruitment, postgraduate, alumni. Four
            integrations had to land cleanly: AIMS, Mulesoft, Marketo and
            SugarCRM.
          </p>

          <h3>The approach</h3>
          <p>
            End-to-end delivery of a Sitecore headless CMS transformation,
            alongside concurrent senior strategic advisory to the director group
            on digital strategy, technology roadmap, innovation priorities and
            transformation sequencing across a complex multi-campus environment.
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>
              Managed vendor procurement for the platform and the implementation
              partner - structured evaluation, commercial negotiation and
              contract
            </li>
            <li>Delivered more than 450 study, discipline and course pages</li>
            <li>
              Landed integrations across AIMS, Mulesoft, Marketo and SugarCRM
            </li>
            <li>
              Advised the director group on digital strategy, roadmap and
              transformation sequencing
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3>The outcome</h3>
          <p>
            Corporate website went live on time and without incident. Post
            go-live support requests were minimal - a strong indicator of
            release quality for a program of this scope. The five functional
            stakeholder groups remained aligned through to go-live.
          </p>
        </div>

        <aside class="case-aside">
          <div class="case-metrics">
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">450+</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Study, discipline and course pages delivered.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">4</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Integrations: AIMS, Mulesoft, Marketo, SugarCRM.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">5</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Functional groups aligned through delivery.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">0</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">Cutover incidents at go-live.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="case-meta">
            <dl>
              <dt>Client</dt><dd>CQUniversity</dd>
              <dt>Sector</dt><dd>Higher Education</dd>
              <dt>Role</dt><dd>Program Manager, Digital Engagement</dd>
              <dt>Year</dt><dd>2021-2023</dd>
              <dt>Platform</dt><dd>Sitecore headless CMS</dd>
            </dl>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CASE 05 - CYBER SECURITY CRC -->
  <section id="case-05" class="case-section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="case-header">
        <div class="case-num">05</div>
        <div>
          <div class="case-tags">
            <span class="tag tag--ochre">Concurrent Delivery</span>
            <span class="tag">National Security Research</span>
            <span class="tag">Cybersecurity Uplift</span>
          </div>
          <h2 class="case-title">
            Two enterprise programs. <em>Immovable deadlines.</em> One national-security
            research environment.
          </h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="case-body">
        <div class="case-narrative">
          <h3>The situation</h3>
          <p>
            The Cyber Security Cooperative Research Centre - a government-funded
            research centre dedicated to advancing Australia's national cyber
            security capability - needed delivery discipline established and two
            concurrent enterprise transformation programs run to fixed
            deadlines, in an environment where security governance and
            compliance requirements were non-negotiable.
          </p>

          <h3>The approach</h3>
          <p>
            Engaged as Head of Project Delivery. Established the operating
            cadence. Then ran the two programs in parallel:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Salesforce CRM transformation</strong> using Agile delivery
              practices - iterative development, business engagement, user acceptance
              testing, training and full organisational rollout
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Microsoft O365 E5 enterprise security uplift</strong> - implementing
              Defender, Information Protection, BitLocker, Intune and advanced threat
              analytics across the organisation
            </li>
          </ul>

          <p>
            Delivery was managed across three distinct partner types
            simultaneously: internal teams, a virtual CISO and managed service
            partners - each operating under different commercial arrangements
            and reporting lines.
          </p>

          <h3>The outcome</h3>
          <p>
            Both programs delivered on time. Security uplift completed within
            the compliance envelope appropriate to a national-security research
            context. Delivery discipline established for the wider organisation.
          </p>
        </div>

        <aside class="case-aside">
          <div class="case-metrics">
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">2</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Concurrent enterprise programs to fixed deadlines.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">3</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Partner types coordinated: internal, vCISO, MSP.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">E5</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Microsoft O365 cybersecurity uplift completed.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="case-metric-num">CRM</div>
              <div class="case-metric-label">
                Salesforce transformation delivered Agile.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="case-meta">
            <dl>
              <dt>Client</dt><dd>Cyber Security CRC</dd>
              <dt>Sector</dt><dd>National security research</dd>
              <dt>Role</dt><dd>Head of Project Delivery</dd>
              <dt>Year</dt><dd>2020-2021</dd>
              <dt>Platforms</dt><dd>Salesforce, Microsoft O365 E5</dd>
            </dl>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ENGAGE -->
  <section class="engage">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="engage__grid">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow">Your engagement next</div>
          <h2 style="margin-top:1.25rem;">
            Bring us in <em>before</em> the next board meeting.
          </h2>
          <p class="lead" style="margin-top:1.5rem;">
            The next case study could be yours. Most Lavelle engagements start
            the same way: a confidential thirty-minute conversation about what's
            not moving, followed by a written diagnostic if the problem warrants
            it. No pitch deck, no obligation, no sales workshop disguised as a
            meeting.
          </p>
          <div class="hero__ctas" style="margin-top:2.5rem;">
            <a href="/contact" class="btn btn--primary">
              Request an engagement conversation <span class="btn__arrow"
                >→</span
              >
            </a>
            <a
              href="/consulting"
              class="btn"
              style="background:transparent; color:var(--bone); border:1px solid var(--bone);"
            >
              See consulting services
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <ul class="engage__list">
          <li>
            <a href="/contact?topic=brief"
              ><span>Submit a brief (RFP / EOI)</span><span>→</span></a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="/contact?topic=call"
              ><span>Book a 30-minute call with Sky</span><span>→</span></a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="/contact?topic=capability"
              ><span>Request a capability statement</span><span>→</span></a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="/contact?topic=panel"
              ><span>Government panel listing</span><span>→</span></a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .case-section {
    padding: clamp(3rem, 6vw, 5rem) 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
  }
  .case-section:last-of-type {
    border-bottom: none;
  }
  .case-header {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
    align-items: end;
  }
  @media (min-width: 880px) {
    .case-header {
      grid-template-columns: auto 1fr;
      gap: 3rem;
    }
  }
  .case-num {
    font-family: "Fraunces", serif;
    font-size: clamp(3.5rem, 7vw, 6rem);
    font-weight: 300;
    color: var(--ochre);
    line-height: 0.9;
    font-variation-settings: "opsz" 144;
    font-style: italic;
  }
  .case-tags {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }
  .tag {
    font-size: var(--micro);
    letter-spacing: 0.15em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--sage);
    padding: 0.3rem 0.7rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--rule);
    border-radius: 999px;
  }
  .tag--ochre {
    color: var(--ochre);
    border-color: var(--ochre);
  }
  .case-title {
    font-family: "Fraunces", serif;
    font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 3.2vw, 2.6rem);
    font-weight: 400;
    line-height: 1.08;
    letter-spacing: -0.018em;
    max-width: 24ch;
  }
  .case-title em {
    color: var(--ochre);
    font-style: italic;
  }
  .case-body {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 3rem;
  }
  @media (min-width: 980px) {
    .case-body {
      grid-template-columns: 1.4fr 1fr;
      gap: 5rem;
    }
  }
  .case-narrative h3 {
    font-family: "DM Sans", sans-serif;
    font-size: var(--micro);
    letter-spacing: 0.2em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--ochre);
    font-weight: 500;
    margin: 2rem 0 0.75rem;
  }
  .case-narrative h3:first-child {
    margin-top: 0;
  }
  .case-narrative p {
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    max-width: 62ch;
  }
  .case-narrative ul {
    list-style: none;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }
  .case-narrative ul li {
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
  }
  .case-narrative ul li::before {
    content: "-";
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--ochre);
  }
  .case-aside {
    align-self: start;
    position: sticky;
    top: 100px;
  }
  .case-metrics {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 1.5rem 2rem;
    padding: 2rem;
    background: var(--paper);
    border: 1px solid var(--rule);
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }
  .case-metric-num {
    font-family: "Fraunces", serif;
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 3.5vw, 2.6rem);
